reviews.review_text: Super plush AUD. The "This Day in History" dragnet has caught another one.  So glad we have this feature, otherwise I would just get lost over the years in this vault.  Brilliant audience recording. Just right.  Brilliant show.   For Friend of the Devil fans....this one is a gem.  Jerry's voice....mmmm, good.  Reminds me of the Dead Set version, which I hold as a high watermark for that tune.  That Bertha>Playin opener really gets it going in the second set.  Within the first words of Ship of Fools, you are reminded again how great Garcia's voice is, on this night. One caution--there is an obnoxious dork who is yelling Saint Stephen multiple times during the first of the sick Playin' in the Band jams.  WTF?
first show this was my 1st show! great recording, i closed my eyes and it took me back there!uh oh flashbacks! lol thanks guys!! Great show!

Solid show This was my first show and I have never heard a recording of it before.  I remember very little about the actual music since the scene was new to me and a little overwhelming, but listening to this reveals that it was a very solid show for it's time.  Nothing amazing, but solid and a great introduction to the many shows which would follow.  The main thing that struck me most about The Spectrum was how many people never even went into the stadium itself, just danced up and down the cavernous hallways all evening.  I scalped a ticket which was supposed to be stage right but instead was way up and behind the stage, literally the worst seat in the house.  Caveat emptor, even at a Dead show!

My first show too This was also my first show. 16 years old and two hits of red mirco-dot…Wow!!!  Like aadelma said, "I remember very little about the actual music since the scene was new to me".  I lost my friends as soon as we got inside. So I figured I’d go to where our seats were. They were also behind the stage but lower down. I remember dancing with some heads and getting high.  Lots of elbow room and a very mellow scene.  Great first set and a wacky second set. My main recollection of the show was the parking lot scene and the fact that it snowed after the show. I was on a plane to New Orleans the next morning and caught Rush in Biloxi, MS on April 7th.

Better than I recall Was kinda high that night, but both me and my friend remember this show as being a real train wreck starting from the beginning of the second set.  Goes to show, you don't ever know . . .

The next night,however, without acid, I still remember as one of the best shows I've ever seen.  Deadnet just announced that 4/6 (with a smattering of 4/5) will be released as the next "Road Trips" entry.

My first show too! Seriously. It was my first show, I think. I know it was a spring tour show, in Philly, with a Jack Straw opener.  And, I remember figuring it out using Deadbase.  After listening to show, I realized that this show is why I like certain sort of sounds and why I have been chasing them ever since.

Spectrum's plectrums
The next night is the big show - one of the top few from '82 - but, as part of a hot tour in general, this is also worthy. There is a unique post-Ship jam into Drums and it's the third show after Jer/Phil switched places. These were their only two shows in Penn in '82, and followed an 11/81 show in Pittsburgh. First Set. From the start Jer is already firing on 8 cylinders. Deep Elem is the first of just two in '82. It's flubby: two verses are skipped and the other two are sung twice, but it's a minor issue in a solid set. After Bobby's Slide Practice™ in Rooster, the rest is money. Althea is calmly slickened; everybody is p  l  a  y  i   n   g. Dewiminna is sloppy-goofy in a fun way. Second Set. The first few secs are missing on the SBD and the official, but Bertha is absolutely on top of the situation, ticking the quasar boxes. It starts a helluva sequence to Playin' and into Ship and Drums. Some setlists list a second Playin', but there isn't one, just a long jam into Drums. This jam is exactly what you get when you say Grateful Dead. Exactly what you want, too. The drummers spend the excursion assuming they have finished steering out onto the parkway of Drums, but Brent and Bobby keep hanging in there. Jer/Phil relinquish to the drummers after 5 :45 mins. Loose in structure, but kewl enough to jot a note home. This is not a pleasant Drums>Space, but the back nine is solid enough. The second Playin' finally shows as a jam out of The Wheel. Jer makes brief work of the solo jam in Wharf, into a vapid Good Lovin'. But they come back for a perfect Dough Knees. 1st Set:  B- 2nd Set: B- Overall = 3½ stars Highlights: Althea - heads down, p l a y i n g Bertha - starting on the topmost Playing in the Band - middle of helluva sequence Ship of Fools - unique jam into Drums Don't Ease Me In - leaving 'em thrilled for the lots SOURCES:The wagner_miller_90496 isn't high qual but it's the best available - the other AUDs are speedy and less dynamic. It does have the second set mislabeled and the patch in Jack Straw is too fast. Presumably a SBD is in the vault, since six songs are on Road Trips v4 n4: Deep Elem, Althea & Man Smart from the 1st set; Bertha>Playin'>Ship (to the start of Drums) from the 2nd.
I’m in the 4th Row I’ll take an AUD like this any day over a SBD.  Just close your eyes and you are right there, beautiful sound!  Love the Friend of the Devil!
